Far more difficult to keep petty warlords from taking the food &amp; medical relief parcels to the blackmarket, instead of to the people who need it.<br>
<br>
There's another way, as well.<br>
 I've mentioned the book (with the awful new-age-wacko sounding title) &quot;the Millennial Project: Colonizing the Galaxy in 8 steps&quot;.<br>
<br>
I personally think Savage had the first couple steps reversed: He wanted to start sea-farming floating cities to feed the Earth and make funding available to allow space industries. Especially since the book, it's been shown that there are several problems with his technology, and achievable methods show less promise than he speculated.<br>
 Space industries seem far more readily avalable, and there's far far more room for profit out there. His order of the steps (Sea first, then space) also sounded too much like trying to solve the problems down here before we go blasting off in our rocket ships.<br>
 Make profits in space industries, to pay for the R&amp;D to build sea cities. Power them with SSPS energy. Note that recieving the power beam at deep equatorial ocean floating cities removes most problems with power beaming: Nobody nearby, to be bothered by the beams. Produce methane for fuel export from water-derived H2 and atmospheric CO2.<br>
<br>
 Produce prodigious amounts of food at the floating cities for export to land.<br>
 He was dead-on about this: Aquaculture farming shows vast promise.<br>
Right now, something like 85% of our seafood is caught at ocean (as opposed to freshwater, shallow coastal, or farmed). Our methods are neolithic, pre-agriculture: go out to where the game is, then clobber it and drag it home.<br>
 We need to advance beyond this to mariculture farming. 75% of the planetary surface is water, 90% of the planetary biomass -the mass of living matter on the planet- is simple organisms in the oceans. Equatorial deep oceans are vast deserts, but a few relatively small areas of upwellings are where most of the sea catch comes from.<br>
 Artficial upwellings at floating sea farm cities could vastly increase our food (far more high value food than most land animals we farm), while not taking up land area.<br>
